		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ca[e]teri loquuntur: ille fluit. Alij
						equitant: ille uolat.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Others speak: that man procedees. Others ride: that man flies.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Solus perpa[e]trat omnia.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The single thing accomplishes everything.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Phocion securis: Demades pugio.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Phocion"/>
					<person name="Demades"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Phocion is the axe: Demades the dagger.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Succinctus: Sed cataphractus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Equipped: but armored.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ea curat prudens Pragmaticus, qua[e] in vsu forensi maximè florent; et regnant
						in causis politicis, publicis, priuatis. Dignum est studio, et praxi, quod 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						pra[e]dominatur.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>A prudent pragmatist cares for those things which greatly flourish in public use; and which reign in political, public, and private causes. It is worthy of study and the practice which predominates.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Turpe est, in pragmatico aliquo puncto ha[e]rere: et Bartholomeo Clerco ipse
						Bodinus Ciphra videbatur; quia non erat Gallicoru[m] Pragmaticoru[m] Princeps.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Jean Bodin"/>
					<person name="Bartholomew Clerke"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>It is foolish to cling to a point in any pragmatic man; and Bodin himself seemed a cipher to Bartholomew Clerke, because he was
				not the prince of French pragmatists.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
